    <!-- http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LaboratoryAnalysisOperation -->


    <owl:Class rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LaboratoryAnalysisOperation">
        <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/ExplorationOperation"/>
        <rdfs:comment>As per D9.1, this term coined as analysis</rdfs:comment>
        <rdfs:comment>D2.1: Laboratory analyses are essential to deepen the characterization of materials present in MWFs, aiming to evaluate their potential for recovery or management.</rdfs:comment>
        <rdfs:comment>This class has been created on the bais D2.2 Section 4.2.1.4


Secondly on the basis of previous data received from the partners:
Q4: The size and extent of the waste
Mineralogy- XRD
SEM/EDS
Electron probe microanalysis (EPMA)
https://confluence.akka.eu/pages/viewpage.action?spaceKey=AKRSCIMIN&amp;title=Data+Analysis+of+WP2+SGS</rdfs:comment>
    </owl:Class>
    


    <!-- http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LandImpact -->


    <owl:Class rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LandImpact">
        <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/EnvironmentalImpact"/>
    </owl:Class>
    


    <!-- http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LeachingOperation -->


    <owl:Class rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LeachingOperation">
        <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/MineralProcessingOperation"/>
        <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">MWEI BREF : Extraction of soluble components from raw materials by the action of a percolating liquid (e.g. water). For example, gold can be extracted by heap 
leaching of a porous ore, or pulverised extractive waste from mineral  processing. Other methods are tank leaching of ore, concentrates or extractive waste from mineral processing and in-situ leaching. Leaching may also be an unwanted process leading to polluted drainage (see &quot;leachate&quot;). Bio-leaching is a particular form of leaching involving living organisms</rdfs:comment>
    </owl:Class>
    


    <!-- http://www.semanticweb.org/rajesh.piryani/ontologies/2025/3/SCIMIN_CRM/LegalRestriction -->


